  "articleSummary": "Thearticle argues that most teams consider Algolia ™ too late, without first asking whether their search needs can be satisfied by a static‑site index. It presents Pagefind—a tool that builds a search index directly from the HTML generated at build time—as the default choice for content‑driven sites (blogs, docs, marketing pages, internal handbooks, etc.), emphasizing its simplicity, CDN‑friendly assets, and lack of a separate search service. The piece contrasts this with Algolia (and similar live‑search solutions), which are appropriate only when the index must change independently of deployments—e.g., for live inventory, per‑user permissions, custom ranking, or analytics. Written in an instructive, slightly opinionated tone, the article uses the metaphor of “extra system” versus “single artifact” to frame the decision, targeting developers and product teams responsible for site search architecture.",
